  "response": "The Samsung Galaxy Note 7 battery explosions were primarily caused by design and manufacturing flaws that led to internal short circuits. Here are the key issues:\n\n1. Battery Design Problems:\n- Insufficient space between the battery's positive and negative electrodes\n- Thin separators that could easily be bent or damaged\n- High-density battery design that prioritized compact size over safety\n\n2. Manufacturing Defects:\n- Irregular welding of battery components\n- Inconsistent battery cell production\n- Potential contamination during manufacturing process\n\n3. Specific Technical Causes:\n- Electrode compression causing internal short circuits\n- Thermal runaway (rapid uncontrolled temperature increase)\n- Increased probability of battery separator failure\n\n4. Root Cause Analysis:\n- Initial battery batch from Samsung SDI had structural defects\n- Replacement batteries from another manufacturer also showed similar problems\n- Design constraints that pushed battery performance limits\n\n5. Consequences:\n- Numerous reported incidents of battery overheating and explosions\n- Global recall of all Note 7 devices\n- Significant financial and reputational damage for Samsung\n\nThe fundamental issue was an unsafe battery design that compromised physical separation between battery components, creating conditions for potential short circuits and thermal runaway.",
